{{English contents}}
Sentences come in two main parts: *[[English/Parts of the Sentence/Subjects|Subjects]], that tell what the sentence is about *[[English/Parts of the Sentence/Predicates|Predicates]], that describe the subject These are the two main parts of every sentence.
You may learn about these parts of the sentence, go back to the previous section about [[English/Parts of Speech|parts of speech]], or go on to the next section about [[English/Word Functions|word functions]].
{{stub}}

{{English contents}}

Pronunciation describes '''how''' words and sentences are pronounced.  English is an international language so there is no one correct pronunciation of English.  Pronunciation of words is different between countries and also inside countries - pronunciation of words is very different in many parts of the [[w:United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] (See [[English/Differences between British English and American English|Differences between British and American English]])

English pronunciation is related to the history of English.  The two main roots of English are [[w:Anglo-Saxon|Anglo-Saxon]] (like German) and [[w:Latin|Latin]].  This means that most words in English sound a little like German or Latin.  Many short words come from Anglo-Saxon (good, but, wife) and have [[wikt:rough|rough]] sounds that are made in the [[w:throat|throat]].  Many long words come from Latin (provision, amiable, analysis) and have [[wikt:smooth|smooth]] sounds made by the [[w:tongue|tongue]] and [[w:lips|lips]].

{{stub}}

