{{English contents}}
An '''indirect object''' is a second object in a sentence.  It receives the action of the [[English/Parts of Speech/Verbs|verb]] only indirectly.  There can only be an indirect object if there is already a [[English/Word Functions/Direct Objects|direct object]].

''We gave the teacher our tests.''

In the above sentence ''we'' is the subject of the sentence, ''our tests'' is the direct object (the thing that was given), and ''the teacher'' is the indirect object.  This is because the teacher took the tests (receiving the action), but was not the thing given (our tests).

Indirect objects are often used in sentences with verbs like ''tell'', ''give'', ''ask'', ''buy'', ''sell'' and many other common verbs.
{{stub}}

{{ctt|About Claims}}
''Claims'' are something someone claims. For instance, claims like ''I was in Trenton yesterday morning'', or ''The bus leaves at 10 o'clock.''

